      <title>Hydrogen-powered flying taxi produces zero emissions</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANMassachusetts-based Alaka'i Technologies has developed a hydrogen-powered air vehicle called Skai that uses six rotors and performs vertical takeoffs and landings.The aircraft also sports an airframe parachute in case if several of its props fail.According to the company's website, Skai has a range of 400 miles and will be able to remain airborne for approximately four hours. It has a capacity of five passengers, including the captain.Skai will be powered by hydrogen fuel cells, which emit only pure water, according to Skai's project page.Hydrogen fuel cells consists of compressed hydrogen which reacts with an oxidizing agent such as oxygen to create energy. These cells have a greater weight-energy density than batteries and fossil fuels.The aircraft will initially be piloted. However, the company said it is looking into remote or autonomous options.Reuters reports the company is currently waiting to receive certification from Federal Aviation Administration. Steve Hanvey, the CEO of Alaka'i Technologies, told Reuters that they expect to receive certification by the end of 2020. He added that they plan to start selling the aircraft in the beginning of 2021. The company has yet to announce the price of the aircraft.  RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The aircraft, how it takes off and an airframe parachute2. The range of Skai and its capacity3. How the aircraft will be powered4. The aircraft has a pilot, though the company may include remote or autonomous options in the futureVOICEOVER (in English): "Massachusetts-based Alaka'i Technologies has developed a hydrogen-powered air vehicle called Skai that uses six rotors and performs vertical takeoffs and landings.""The aircraft also consists of an airframe parachute in case if several of its props fail.""According to the company's website, Skai has a range of 400 miles and will be able to remain airborne for approximately four hours.""It has a capacity of five passengers, including the captain.""Skai will be powered by hydrogen fuel cells, which only emits pure water, according to Skai's project page." "Hydrogen fuel cells consists of compressed hydrogen which reacts with an oxidizing agent such as oxygen to create energy.""According to Forbes, these cells have a greater weight-energy density than batteries and fossil fuels.""The aircraft will initially be piloted, however, the company said it is looking into remote or autonomous options."SOURCES: Inhabitat, New Atlas, Design Boom, Reuters, Uncrate, Skai, Forbeshttps://inhabitat.com/the-skai-hydrogen-powered-aircraft-produces-zero-emissions/https://newatlas.com/alakai-skai-hydrogen-vtol-air-taxi/59911/https://www.designboom.com/technology/alakai-technologies-skai-evtol-hydrogen-fuel-cell-flying-car-03-20-2019/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-hydrogen-aircraft/hydrogen-powered-flying-vehicle-touted-as-southern-california-traffic-tonic-idUSKCN1T0078https://uncrate.com/skai-zero-emission-aircraft/https://skai.co/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeremybogaisky/2019/08/14/zeroavia-alakai-hydrogen-fuel-cell/#65a4d88f18aa***]]></description>
